1500","1565":"1565","1455":"1455","1496":"1496","after 1485":"na 1485","1418":"1418","1449":"1449","about 1472":"circa 1472","Hunstanton, Norfolk, England":"Hunstanton, Norfolk, England","Slaidburn, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Slaidburn, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Calais, Artois/Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Calais, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Frankrijk","Kimberley, Norfolk, England":"Kimberley, Norfolk, England"},"en":{"1449–1493":"1449–1493","1455–1500":"1455–1500","1450–1496":"1450–1496","1426–1481":"1426–1481","1490–1565":"1490–1565","1424–1468":"1424–1468","1418–1480":"1418–1480","10 March 1481":"10 March 1481","1450":"1450","1493":"1493","1481":"1481","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","15 May 1468":"15 May 1468","1426":"1426","1468":"1468","1424":"1424","1500":"1500","1565":"1565","1455":"1455","1496":"1496","after 1485":"after 1485","1418":"1418","1449":"1449","about 1472":"about 1472","Hunstanton, Norfolk, England":"Hunstanton, Norfolk, England","Slaidburn, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Slaidburn, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Calais, Artois/Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Calais, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France","Kimberley, Norfolk, England":"Kimberley, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Radcliffe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Ratliff  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ratliff","meanings":["English (Suffolk): habitational name from one or more of the places so named, such as Radcliffe (Lancashire), Radcliffe on Trent and Ratcliffe on Soar (both Nottinghamshire), Radclive (Buckinghamshire), Ratcliffe Culey and Ratcliffe on the Wreake (both Leicestershire), Ratclyffe in Clyst Hydon, Ratcliffes in Thorverton, and Ratcliffes in Broad Clyst (all Devon), Ratcliff in Stepney (Middlesex), and Rackley in Compton Bishop (Somerset). The placenames derive from Old English <i>rēad</i> ‘red’ + <i>clif</i> ‘cliff, bank, steep slope’ (see also   Rutley  ). A family of the name <i>Radcliffe</i> trace their descent from Sir Nicholas <i>de Radclyffe</i>. He is said to have been a knight who held the major of Radcliffe in Lancashire and served Roger de Poitou, Baron de Marsey in the 11th century."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":6,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert Radcliffe was born in 1449, in Kimberley, Norfolk, England, his father, Richard Radcliffe, was 26 and his mother, Is